NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: Beware of subscription traps. The quality of the oil seems good, and the taste is good too. Unfortunately, I misplaced my ID card during the blood test. This meant that my expensive blood test was null and void. They didn't help me any further. I then tried to cancel my subscription at the end of the 6 months.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: Beware of Eprimo. I ended up there via check24. This morning I received a new offer. My payment went up from €98 to €428. I've just canceled everything and will look for a reputable electricity provider.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: The worst crap, absolute rip-off. No real help, just a subscription trap.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: Be careful with the 6-month subscription! It says in advance that you can cancel in the customer portal one month before the subscription expires! Unfortunately that wasn't possible... I sent an email to the support team in good time - they confirmed the cancellation. Nevertheless, I received two more deliveries and the money was debited from my account... Today, two months later, I'm still emailing the unhelpful and unfortunately not very competent lady from the support team. Competent information cannot be obtained over the phone because no precautions have been taken. The product itself (Pure Arctic oil) didn't have any significant effect on me that would justify the high price. Recommendation to Eqology: - simplify the method for canceling the 6-month subscription. This should always be quick and easy to see in the customer portal. (Builds trust) Create the option to get information over the phone if the support team is stuck.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I've been a customer for over a year – and quite honestly: What's going on here is a complete disgrace. The customer service is disrespectful, incompetent, and completely disinterested. A simple email with three clear questions? You might get one of them half-answered – and in a tone that's anything but friendly. On the phone, you're treated rudely, sometimes abusively, often in bad German, completely unprofessional. It seems like a cheap external call center that has nothing to do with the company itself – absolutely no solution-orientation, no empathy, no responsibility. Promised services like 3FF or bonus payments are either not implemented at all or handled so non-transparently that you, as a customer, are completely in the dark. Any further queries? Are they ignored or dismissed. I now know several business partners who report the same thing – some actively warn against the company. And then the reviews here: To be honest – good reviews seem questionable once you've experienced for yourself how things work internally. They advertise sustainability, environmental protection, and high-quality oil – but no one cares whether the customers are doing well or whether the processes even work. The main thing is that it's network marketing, everyone makes their commission – but no one takes responsibility. No wonder everything looks polished as long as the only thing you're supposed to do is sell. But if there's a problem, you're suddenly completely on your own. Bottom line: Buy your oil elsewhere. Here you get nice advertising slogans, but no real support, no reliability, no honesty. This is a big sales machine – more show than substance. It's not contemporary – and certainly not worth supporting.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I canceled my eqology subscription on time. I'm now receiving another shipment of the gold oil and vitamin D3 tablets. But I keep getting messages saying I can't cancel yet, and another time I'm sent a cancellation confirmation. Then they say again they need my exact details, even though they have them. It's unbelievable. So I'll see if I can cancel. If not, I'll take legal action. This isn't honest or customer-friendly.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: Beware of Eqology! I was recently charged for an additional bottle and sent it to me. I spent ages on the phone and texting customer service to get the whole thing returned. Now, instead of the gold oil I paid for, they only sent me the regular oil. After complaining, I had to go through a complicated process. Fill out a form, days later they wanted photos as proof, now I have to take everything to the post office and send it back. Only after everything has been checked will I get my correct bottle. Eqology is by no means customer-friendly. It seems they're trying to squeeze even more money out of the customer.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: If I could, I wouldn't give it a star at all. They lure you into a subscription without even realizing it! Cancellation is only possible with a medical certificate or a €60 fine!

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: None of the things advertised in the presentations happened after taking the products. Quite the opposite! I stopped taking the Gold Oil and the D3 K 2 capsules exactly three weeks later! The reasons for this were high blood pressure, depression, extreme fatigue (I almost fell asleep while driving), shortness of breath, lack of motivation, etc. I can only recommend avoiding taking these products without medical supervision. Every human organism is unique and reacts differently accordingly. I will now have the product tested in an independent laboratory.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I was recommended the product (Omega-3 oil and K2/D3 capsules) by my gynecologist, and I signed the "contract" there. I actually thought my K2/D3 levels would also be tested, but this didn't happen, only my Omega-3/Omega-6 levels. I then had my K2/D3 levels checked by my family doctor. According to these guidelines, my K2 level was too high, so I shouldn't take it anymore (according to the Eqology overview, however, with my K2 data, I do have a K2 requirement, which I find very interesting, so I'll also have my Omega-3 requirements checked). I returned the unused K2/D3 capsules; apparently, they never arrived at the warehouse (I've enclosed my invoice), and therefore no refund is possible... I've now canceled the subscription. Since the 6 months aren't up yet, I'll probably be charged a cancellation fee of €60. Overall, it's very tedious, but the money is quickly debited from your account!

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: Apparently, distributors are forced to make money! My colleague is a distributor, and she's not just trying to sell the oil subscription, concealing the fact that it's a subscription, but also recruiting new distributors. Initially, they listened to her, but now they slam the office door when they hear the woman leaving her own office. A "I'm not interested!" isn't accepted. Unbelievable! No one in the company wants to work with this woman anymore; she even chats up customers and pushes the oil on them.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I've been regularly ordering products from this company for a year now, and I can say that the quality of the products is really good. Unfortunately, the customer service is so poor that I've decided to order elsewhere. A huge number of errors occur, and contact is incredibly difficult – you often have to wait over a week for a response, and even then, many questions are either inadequately answered or not answered at all. My emails were ignored several times, and when I contacted them by phone, communication was difficult because the German I spoke was often poor. What was particularly disappointing was that I was even insulted by customer service once. With high-quality, expensive products, professional, helpful, and respectful customer service should be a given. Unfortunately, this is not reflected in this company at all, which is ultimately the reason why I decided to stop ordering from them.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: The products are generally fine, but I canceled the subscription because they're overpriced. You can find the same oils and products elsewhere for about a third of the price. I also had to pay €60 to cancel the subscription, which I find unreasonable.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: It's all about selling a monthly subscription. Stay away from it!

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: After several difficult attempts, my subscription was canceled, according to an email from Eqology. I was asked to return the products they sent me for a refund and enclose an invoice (the amount of €135 had already been debited from my account). There was no invoice in the package, nor did I receive one by email, even after I requested one. I have now returned the package without it and hope this will still work. I'm curious to see if a refund will actually follow. I've never experienced this before: a customer not receiving an invoice (for an amount they've already paid).

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: Beware of disguised subscriptions! No transparency about the brokers, the entire concept is not reputable. Cancellations are only answered after several days. Partial refunds are only given upon request.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I'm really very disappointed. My gynecologist recommended the product to me without telling me that I was signing up for a subscription. I also didn't receive any information to log into a user account. I sent an email to Eqology that same evening, requesting to cancel the subscription (I was then informed by email that this should be possible within 14 days). I also contacted Eqology by phone with a request to cancel. I was told there was no customer account with my email address. The employee was also quite unfriendly and almost ridiculed my request. A few days later, however, I had a hefty €135 debit from my account. I wrote another email, but there was no response. It can't be that I sign a contract and want to cancel it on the same day, but it's not possible. I assume I'll receive the products now. If I send them back, I might end up like some people here, where the package doesn't arrive. I was already a customer of Eqology a year ago and was very satisfied, but apparently customer service is no longer a priority here. I fear I'm now "trapped" in a subscription that, with luck, won't let me get out of for another six months. I look forward to a response from you, although I assume I'll be referred to support, where I won't receive a response or will be ignored (which I find the worst of all).

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I ordered a product as a single delivery. The "Subscription" and "Single Delivery" options are very easy to distinguish, so I'm 100% sure I chose the single delivery option. Nevertheless, less than a month later, I received an email informing me that my "order" had been shipped. The invoice amount had already been debited from my account, and the delivery could no longer be stopped. Although I was offered a free return and refund, all of this involved a lot of effort: For example, I have to reply to an email from the shipping warehouse with my bank details, which I should receive as soon as the return arrived there. Thus, I am providing Eqology with a free credit, in my case only €130. If the company pulls this scam on numerous customers, and many of them simply accept it, it likely means significant profits. In any case, I was not offered any compensation for the effort I incurred. My consequences: I will no longer order anything from Eqology and can only advise against ordering from this company that engages in unfair business practices.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I was recruited as a business partner by a good friend, a naturopathic practitioner. Given my high profile, this was a good business model for a good product for everyone involved. However, my first order as a new business partner was disappointing. The packaging was unsealed, flimsy, partially damaged, and the contents were not protected against impact. It was scattered in a haphazard manner, with brochures scattered about, measuring cups and pens all scattered in a jumbled manner, as if simply thrown in. Multiple calls to support (at the specified times) were unsuccessful, and the recorded message ended with a reference to the support email. My email initially went unanswered, and only after days did I receive a response stating that the packaging was "to protect the product from contamination and damage," which was indeed the case. After requesting a return label and terminating the business partnership because this packaging was unacceptable for a product in the "high-price segment," I received an email confirming my acknowledgement and reversing the transaction. Not a word of regret, not a single apology, or explanation as to why the shipment was not correct (that could have changed my mind as a business partner)!!! In short, I'm glad I don't have a business with such an unprofessional company, because I can't expect my partners (especially those in the exclusive business) to endure this. I don't know if this is in line with EQology's general guidelines or if it's a problem with the German sales department. EQology would do well to review its business partnerships and improve the service it provides to its business partners. Until this happens, I unfortunately cannot recommend this company. Communication between the company and business partners in the "high-price segment" must be seamless. I wouldn't buy a quality watch in a plastic bag, for example. Unfortunately, there was no way to communicate directly. By phone: endless hold with a reference to the support email. The response from the support email took days, and it was IMPERSONAL!!!

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I first heard about the product on November 14, 2024, at a promotional presentation in Munich. The doctor from Austria who gave the presentation on Omega 3 was good. Unfortunately, the participants were only able to taste the regular oil and not the expensive gold version. Since I also tried the regular oil, I assumed that the premium version (Pure Arctic Oil Gold) would taste just as good. I then ordered the premium version and was shocked at how bad the oil tasted. For me, the oil is not intended for humans, but for engines. You can't possibly drink a product like that. After further online research, I was even more shocked when I discovered that this oil even received an award from taste-institute.com in 2022 for its good taste !!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!???????? The EQOLGY partner suggested exchanging the gold version for the regular oil, even though the gold version is significantly more expensive. He refused to offer a better suggestion because of the price difference, and I had to try to sell the oil myself to someone who couldn't care less about the taste. Then I realized that I couldn't trust EQOLOGY and its partners, because I might have spent €200 for nothing. My overall experience was super, super bad, and I deeply regret even going to the lecture. I wouldn't recommend the oil to anyone.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I was also recommended the company by a naturopath. I'm studying business administration and am an entrepreneur myself, so luckily I'm not naive enough to support such a scheme. 1. The company operates a pyramid scheme. The naturopath told me that if I could recommend the subscriptions to three friends, I would get my money back. 2. The prices are pure rip-off. No process/refinement/pseudo-marketing legitimizes selling people omega-3 oil for over 1,000 euros a year. I would strongly recommend everyone to stay away from this company. The website is very well implemented, and the pseudo-scientific arguments may guarantee legitimacy to many visitors, but there's nothing behind them. Simply buy your omega-3 for 1/20 of the price at a pharmacy or elsewhere online. It will be good for your wallet and you won't notice any physical difference.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: Absolute rip-off, the "subscription model" is a subscription trap!! Hands off!

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I was practically talked into buying this product by a nice alternative practitioner who supposedly has nothing to do with this company. After I canceled my order, I promptly received a call from the nice lady. She now has one less patient. The cancellation took place several weeks ago and was confirmed via email. There's still no trace of the money. It will probably end with a chargeback. This company has very shady business practices. I'd stay away from it.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: This company is completely dubious. I strongly advise everyone not to order anything from this company. You're falling into a subscription trap. I had a very bad experience. The subscription couldn't be canceled, only for a fee of €60. Despite paying this amount, another delivery was made. I then returned the product, Omega 3 oil, to the sender's address. Today I received the message "Package was not delivered, please contact..."! I highly recommend staying away.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I've been taking the regular oil since summer 2023. Now I've found out that the DHA value MUST be twice as high as the EPA value. And that's absolutely not the case. So I've paid for a year for nothing. Only the Omega 3 Gold oil has the correct values. And I think it's dubious to sell people vitamin D (too low a dosage and far too expensive) at a totally overpriced price. For that price, I can get 5,000 units on Amazon, 365 of which cost around €20. According to my alternative practitioner, my vitamin D3/K2 is perfect for me. And it's also dubious not to test customers' vitamin D levels beforehand. Some have levels that are too low and would need 10 times the amount, and for those whose levels are too high, it's too dangerous to sell them! That's actually a criminal offense. And now to me: since January 24th (my values ​​are perfect) I've only had inflammations that won't go away. I'm constantly sick and I'm feeling worse and worse. I've now stopped taking the oil. Something's not right here. I have 10 bottles left and will try to sell them on, but my consultant won't take it back. She only wants to swap them, but I'm really disappointed because I spent so much money and I've only felt worse since then. You can imagine how I spent a year's worth of money. I persuaded two people to buy it too, and they stopped taking it too. I bought their oil back because I was embarrassed, and now I'm stuck with all that oil. So, to repeat... the ingredients aren't as they should be. The DHA/EPA is wrong!

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: The business practices are opaque, and the cancellation options are full of pitfalls. This creates a fundamental distrust of the product.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: A dubious company, a rip-off. They initially perform a blood test that you never see. The product gave me severe diarrhea and nausea. The consultant assured me I could cancel the subscription, which they also kept secret. After some time, I received this horrible stuff again, along with a debit. I contacted the consultant again, and she said she would take care of it... Nothing happened. This "company" is unbelievable. STAY AWAY FROM THEM, I CAN ONLY ADVISE YOU!!!!!

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: Unfortunately, I absolutely cannot recommend this company. The customer service is abysmal. I noticed that they're only interested in selling and don't put people first. There's a complete lack of transparency in the contract and terms and conditions, and only afterward do you realize that you're bound to unexpected and disadvantageous conditions. An extremely disappointing experience – I'll definitely never shop here again.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: This "subscription" is worse than any ringtone subscription (which weren't banned for nothing). Even if you can log into the customer account, you can't find any(!) information about the term or cancellation policy. Not even after clicking through several pages of FAQs. I then canceled via the contact form for the EARLIEST possible date. They weren't interested at all. Customer service fobbed me off with some boilerplate text. However, under German law, a cancellation that hasn't been objected to is considered accepted after 14 days. If Eqology sees it differently, I'll let the consumer protection agency and my lawyer sort it out. Anyone with a good product doesn't need such dubious games, which is why I no longer trust the supposedly oh-so-great fish oil.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I received goods in June, even though I canceled my order and the cancellation was confirmed. I then returned them at my own expense on June 14, 2024. Eqology also confirmed that the goods had supposedly arrived in an interim warehouse, even though I used the specified return address. Since June, I've been receiving reminders from Klarna asking me to pay the invoice, now threatening to contact a debt collection agency. Despite numerous emails to Eqology support, nothing has happened so far other than promises that the matter will be taken care of.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I bought the product with a subscription and overlooked the fine print; that was my mistake. What really disappointed me, however, was that after a surprisingly positive test result in the first month, I wasn't given the option to cancel the subscription free of charge, and I didn't receive any response or support from my advisor when I asked how to handle this. According to the analysis, I'm getting enough Omega 3. Why can't you react competently and professionally in this rare case? I'm a yoga teacher and alternative practitioner and would have liked to recommend the product, but I'm now put off by the way customer problems are handled. So, unfortunately, I can't recommend it, even though the product seems high-quality—what a shame!

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: Unfortunately, trust is being abused. The word "subscription" is NOT mentioned in the sales pitch!!! If you don't take the time to really read everything you sign, you'll be in for a nasty surprise! Furthermore, when I found out I'd signed a 6-month subscription, I wanted to cancel the subscription straight away. FALSE! They only accept cancellations before the second-to-last delivery! (Which is certainly not according to German law) Then I canceled again and they wanted a 60 Euro cancellation fee! I then threatened to call a lawyer. Then my cancellation went through without a fee. From the salesperson to the company - RIP-OFF! If the product is good, why such shady business practices?

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I can't recommend the subscription, and unfortunately, that has nothing to do with trusting customers. Why do I have to sell my product by subscription? Lucky for those who like it - the lemon flavor was too strong for me! I heard on a podcast that it doesn't taste of fish at all and is very digestible. Perhaps my taste buds are too strong; I wouldn't have been able to dress a salad with it. I wanted to cancel the subscription and return the unopened bottle (you get two to start with) - but now I had to pay a large sum just to get out of the 6-month subscription! Replies within 48 hours? NO! I'm disappointed with this kind of service! The product is definitely the best on the market - I don't want to dispute that! I still recommend a single order as a first step - because the consequences if you don't like it are unfortunately serious!

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I would have liked to cancel my subscription within the cancellation period, as I unfortunately cannot tolerate the product. The subscription was set up by my gynecologist and the user name was obviously not the same as the one she gave me. Since then I have been unable to access my customer account. I keep writing and then I get a link to reset my password, which is pointless if I don't have a user name. Now I have a user name but I still can't log in. I have no idea what the problem is. No reply to my email!!! No one is reachable by phone. You should look up the opening times on the website.... I feel like I'm in a bad movie. So I'm tied in for half a year and can neither access the site nor cancel it or do anything else. I would have loved to voice my anger to a real person, but the people who take turns answering my emails unfortunately don't have a phone number... Very disappointing, depressing, wastes time and nerves, this company is definitely not contributing to my health. I now expect an immediate response and an immediate cancellation of my subscription. Of course I will share my displeasure with my gynecologist. I assume that I am not the only one who has had such an experience with the company.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I've been trying to cancel my subscription for a month, but my sales representative keeps telling me to stop or putting me off. I can't take the oil or the collagen. They give me heartburn, and the fishy smell disgusts me. How can I cancel after about three months if I don't have a contract?

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I was persuaded to place an order by an Eqology employee over the phone, but immediately canceled the order because the sale seemed very dubious to me. I received confirmation of the order cancellation, but the goods were still shipped to me. I returned everything to the return address that same day. DHL confirmed delivery. Even after three weeks, I have not received confirmation of the return; instead, I have received reminders from Klarna. I specified bank transfer as the payment method, not Klarna. I don't know why this ended up with Klarna. I have since sent several emails to support. I still haven't received confirmation of the cancellation.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: Stay away...Cancellation is almost impossible. I was charged €29.95 on May 13th for cancellation, and now they want another €60 for cancellation. It's a complete rip-off. I'm going to contact Consumer Protection. It's a disgrace.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I can only advise against it. This is worse than the ringtone subscriptions, which were banned at some point. Firstly, depending on your body weight, you consume at least a full tablespoon of oil (which consists mainly of olive oil). This is your entire daily fat requirement, especially if you're trying to lose weight at the same time. The oil is sold on a subscription basis. This subscription lasts for at least six months and must be canceled after that. It's almost impossible to cancel. You're supposed to call a number in the UK if you want to cancel. I'm still waiting for confirmation of the cancellation email I sent to customer service. According to the website, Eqology reserves the right to charge a cancellation fee of EUR 60.00. I wouldn't sign up for such a subscription again.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: The fact that no payment was made for the last delivery was not communicated by EQ (as usual): No email, no payment request, simply no delivery... We've repeatedly said: support is virtually nonexistent. Now the delivery has been made, and payment was made immediately via PayPal, but the glass bottles were defective.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: And the next shipment, too, is unreliable. My online order simply states "FAILED," with no message from EQ customer service (which apparently doesn't exist) explaining why the shipment failed again. I strongly advise against ordering these products; delivery is a hassle, and replies to emails sometimes take up to 10 days. I'm happy to be able to cancel the subscription, which you have to sign up for, but that only works after 6 months.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: My caregiver advised me to give my baby the oil, as rapeseed oil wouldn't be sufficient. Since the packaging states that you should discuss taking it with your pediatrician, I did. He clearly advised against it for various reasons, including allergens (a common trigger for food allergies), etc. The oil ended up in the trash—nothing but money.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I learned about this product from a consultant, and she said she was the person to contact for me. I couldn't tolerate the product (constantly burping the fishy smell, nausea). I informed my consultant that I was canceling the product. A month later, the product was sent to me anyway, along with a payment request. My consultant stated that cancellation would only be accepted with a doctor's note! What a disgrace - as this violates my personal privacy. I gave the doctor's note to my consultant and sent the product back, instructing the bank to block the direct debit. Despite this, I received a reminder and an email stating that the product could not be delivered. The way this product is sold is disgraceful. There is no communication, and as a customer, you only have problems. I have now contacted support directly and hope for a quick resolution.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: Unfortunately, customer support is very poor. Questions go unanswered. I signed up for and paid for a 6-month subscription, and already the second delivery (value over €160) hasn't arrived. Questions about this are NOT being answered by support via the website or by email. (Actual delivery date: January 19, 2024) Our oils for the whole family have now run out; we are now supplementing with high-quality linseed oil. If someone at Eqology doesn't make sure my paid delivery arrives promptly, I will switch my family to linseed oil. Better than continuing to be annoyed by EQ's nonexistent customer service.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: A very dubious sales strategy (forced subscription, difficult cancellation). If you cancel the subscription, you're informed that you have to commit to another subscription for at least six months, and even have to buy two bottles in the first month if you want to buy again. I highly recommend against buying anything from such providers.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: You're pressured into a six-month contract or pay twice as much as you'd pay with other providers. The distribution system is similar to Tupperware. The participating doctor who recommends the product apparently earns a share of the profit. Even if the product doesn't work, you remain bound by the contract. But even with the six-month commitment, you pay more than you would for a regular order with a competitor.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I obtained your oil through a distribution partner – I've been purchasing it for two people for two months. Given the expected effects, it should be passed on continuously. Therefore, I'm extremely dissatisfied – it's not sustainable either! Monthly delivery for two people at the same address in two packages = double the postage! Based on the recommended minimum amount of 15ml daily, you need 18 bottles per year. The postage for two people therefore amounts to €212 annually. This is extremely customer-unfriendly. I expect a reputable company to offer a standard choice: a 6-month supply for two people at the same address in one package!

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I've already explored many network marketing sales systems. I don't find the subscriptions customer-oriented. Therefore, I decided to go with a different company without subscription traps and with vegan products.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: Unfortunately, the 3FF program can only be used if each person receives a monthly bottle with a shipping charge of €6.90. For four people, that's about €330 in shipping costs per year. Even people in the same household have to pay double the shipping costs. Instead of receiving the bottles for six months or a year, you're tied to a monthly subscription with high shipping costs. I've now canceled the subscription for everyone because the business practices seem rather dubious to me. I find it very unfortunate how customers are treated here.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I ordered a one-time delivery from my doctor because I wanted to test the product first. Despite choosing the one-time delivery option, I received three deliveries within five weeks (the money was debited before each delivery). I naturally wanted to return the packages and get a refund, but the website states that you have to contact customer service. They are never reachable by phone in Austria (of course, I called several times during the stated service hours). It is not correct that I had a choice to select the delivery frequency or subscription options, or to benefit from any discount. I had never legally signed up for a subscription, just a one-time order. At first, I thought it was a technical error, but since customer service in Austria is not reachable by phone, and there is no option to return a delivery or cancel a subscription in the customer account on the website (which is always the case with reputable companies), it is probably malicious intent on the part of the company to extort money from customers who cannot defend themselves. I can only strongly advise everyone against using Eqology as a business partner—not because the product is bad (I can't judge that), but because their business practices are highly dubious. I have initiated legal action.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: My sales-driven alternative practitioner got me a 6-month Eqology subscription. I think it's too expensive that each shipment will cost me €5.90. Had I known, I would have bought the established Norsan product from the pharmacy, which is also somewhat cheaper. I find it unbelievable that the oil is delivered in plastic bottles, given the promise of quality. A package that was returned three months ago was not charged. They're charging me €43.90 for nothing. That's aggressive, unprofessional, and untrustworthy. There's no button in my Eqology account to cancel the delivery. I can only pause it. That, too, is extremely questionable, annoying, and untrustworthy. I'm curious to see how the cancellation process goes. I could have actually claimed an Omega 3 test from my health insurance. I pay €125 for Eqology. It's my own fault for buying the overpriced product and taking out the subscription. I should have checked it more thoroughly beforehand. I'm more aware now.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I've been trying to cancel my subscription and my husband's for two weeks now. I can't find anywhere where I can cancel my account. I contacted the company and received a vague email in English. It's very difficult for customers to cancel. If you miss the deadline, the subscription is renewed for another six months, and I don't think that's serious!

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: Unfortunately, I only received a response to emails after one to two weeks. My subscription was canceled, and I've been waiting for two months for a refund of the prepaid amount of €124.90. Unfortunately, no response to date. Impossible.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I was actually quite enthusiastic until a family member, who had been taking the oil exactly as directed, showed no improvement in his results after six months. You advertise a money-back guarantee if a certain result isn't reached, but unfortunately, there's no refund. Instead, you have to do a new test! That's simply not okay and impossible, because the results clearly show that the oil had no effect on this person.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: It didn't do anything for me! The cancellation period is ridiculous for such an expensive product if it doesn't help! And now that I'm supposedly able to cancel, no one answers even during service hours! I'm extremely disappointed, and this product cost me far more energy than it gave me!

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: The subscription fee continues to be debited even after the subscription has ended. To avoid being vulnerable to PayPal, the goods continue to be delivered. A fight to get the money back ensues. I don't see any benefit to these products at all. I was actually sick significantly more often than usual while I was taking them. Probably not because of them, but I think it's a waste of money at best, and the hassle I've experienced is definitely not good for my health. I regret ordering them.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: For a period of 8 months, I took the Pure Arctic Oil Lemon and K2+D3 capsules from Eqology. I can't really say much about their effectiveness, as taking them had neither a positive nor a negative effect on my body. After a short break from the subscription, I'm starting again. I received two deliveries within 14 days without having placed the second order. The amount was paid by direct debit. After many emails with Mr. Rühl, who assured me of a smooth refund, including postage costs paid by me, I received the amount I paid for the goods. However, I did not receive the high postage costs to Poland. I received an incredibly rude email in response to my repeated request for a refund. Unfortunately, I haven't heard anything from Eqology since. It's a shame, and I don't recommend it!

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: Hands off. Despite canceling the purchase in writing on the day of the order and revoking the direct debit authorization, a completely different invoice amount was debited from my account before delivery. My correspondence and sending the cancellation of the purchase by mail/registered mail were ignored, and another debit for a different amount was made despite revoking this authorization. A rip-off to the extreme. Dubious.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: What an immoral company! This company made my life hell for several months. Be careful, most of the 5-star reviews here on Trustpilot come from company employees or from those who receive money for recommending products. My advice to you, my fellow consumers: - You have 14 days to return the goods without giving a reason. To do this, you must notify the company in writing. Since they don't respond here, even better: call and write down the number from the recorded call or record it yourself. Then you should get your money back (including shipping costs). Be careful! Eqology does not reimburse shipping costs. I've called them several times, but they act like they're stupid. It wasn't worth the effort to call again. - If Eqology does not refund the amount within 14 days of receiving the goods, you can do the following: The SEPA direct debit can be reversed within 8 weeks of the SEPA direct debit being deducted. Simply go to the bank to do this. Here, too, you should write an email to the company stating that you are doing this now. You are absolutely within your rights. Please note that this only works with SEPA direct debit. Regarding the product: Completely overpriced. Normally, you pay between €15-20 for equivalent products, instead of €60-80 like with Eqology. Eqology has to pay those who recommend its products. Therefore, the price is high, and there are nasty subscription traps. Speaking of subscription traps: Be careful, even if you take out a subscription through a recommender, you will continue to receive monthly products after the six months unless you notify Eqology again in writing that you wish to cancel the subscription. It's best to stay away from the company and save yourself a lot of money, time, effort, and problems.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: Ecology is withdrawing money from my account without my permission and sending me products without me having ordered anything. That's an absolute no-go; you can't sell a good product that way. Furthermore, the website has no imprint and no contact information without registering. The website has thousands of FAQs and dubious return policies. A company that only employs men should be suspicious in the first place. Unfortunately, a friend persuaded me to buy the products, just once, and I gave them my data. A complete mistake! And now they're withdrawing money without my permission and sending me things I didn't order. That's dubious and annoying.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: Subscription trap. The physio sold it to us, and then €500 is gone.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I was not informed that I was taking out a subscription and I did not receive any written documentation!!! When I asked, they said I could definitely cancel after 6 months: I am currently unable to cancel the subscription. The terms and conditions state that you can only cancel after all 6 installments have been paid. In my opinion, this is not at all customer-friendly and also not trustworthy. It is made unnecessarily difficult to cancel the subscription. No reputable company would do that. I would rather order from somewhere else! The price-performance ratio is not enough for me to pay €60 for a small bottle of oil and D3 with k2. Now the 6 months are finally up and I am still being supplied with the expensive product. I CAN ONLY ADVISE AGAINST IT!!!!!!!

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: The product is certainly very good, but about three times as expensive as, for example, Norsan's "Arktis," which is recommended by many health experts. Therefore, my review is entirely based on the less favorable price-performance ratio of currently €60 for 300ml compared to the competition. Or to put it another way: In my opinion, the product would hardly sell through a "regular" retailer. However, with network marketing and direct sales, that's not Eqology's intention. If it were significantly cheaper, I would recommend it and participate in direct sales. But not in this case.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: My alternative practitioner signed a six-month subscription for me. Since I didn't think the price-performance ratio was right for me, and I was worried about canceling my subscription too late, I sent a cancellation notice directly to the service. The response: I can't currently cancel the subscription. The terms and conditions state that you can only cancel after all six installments have been paid. In my opinion, this is completely uncustomer-friendly and also untrustworthy. This makes it unnecessarily difficult to cancel the subscription. No reputable company would do that. I'd rather order from somewhere else!

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I'm a physiotherapist myself and of course know about the positive aspects of Omega 3. However, I find it strange that this oil can prevent or even cure heart attacks, strokes, and other diseases like psoriasis. That makes me a bit more alert and cautious. I tried it anyway. The taste is, to say the least, inedible, and the fact that this oil comes in plastic bottles is very unusual to me (I've only ever seen high-quality oil in glass bottles). And what I find really awful is that I'm constantly being pressured to bring this oil to my patients or colleagues, to refer at least three people, and then I get my oil for free. Honestly, it's not entirely reputable. And the tests aren't entirely credible either. Interpreting internal tests from non-independent laboratories shows that this company is making a lot of money. During my six-month subscription, I personally had constant herpes for almost half the time (I haven't had that in years). And I listen to my body; I couldn't swallow the stuff, neither mixed with food nor in yogurt or anything like that. And let's be honest: spending at least €60 a month on oil is pretty expensive. I don't want a response from support. My "advisor" has put me on pause, but I'm going to distance myself completely from it.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I canceled my contract today, within the deadline. Now I'm curious to see if I'll receive confirmation and if the cancellation will be accepted.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: My experience was unfortunately negative. I took pure omega 3 for 6 months, initially doing a test and then again after 6 months. Unfortunately, the results were worse. The values ​​were: Omega 3 index 4.8%, now 4.6%, Omega 6/Omega 3 ratio 5.7:1, now 15.9:1. I would like to ask you for a plausible explanation. Eqology support responded to my question about a week later! Afterward, I received another email with questions about taking the product. I answered the questions. To date, I have not received an explanation.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: If you're familiar with the term "pyramid scheme," you've come to the right place. First, you're sold a six-month subscription, then you're asked to send a referral to three other people to receive the next delivery free of charge. Absolutely outrageous. If the manufacturers truly believed in the effectiveness of their product, there would be no need for this scam. In total, you end up paying almost €500 (€130 to start with and then €60 each for the next six months). A horrendous price for a completely overpriced product. Thanks for nothing!

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I tried it, unfortunately with a lot of heartburn and stomach pain. I wanted to cancel my subscription, but they insisted on a 6-month contract. Be careful with subscription contracts. Doctors don't write a certificate for dietary supplements, so you're tied to this dubious subscription for at least 6 months. I'll contact consumer protection and spread the word through the media.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: I have to honestly say that my physiotherapist, whom I trusted completely, got me into a subscription that I didn't really want... That wasn't a problem at all, though; I was able to cancel it after six months without any problems. It was my own fault, I can only say. Regarding the quality of the product, I can only say that after about two months, I found taking it so repugnant... So I talked to my kinesiologist about it, and after a test, it became clear that my body wasn't absorbing this product. I switched to a different product (which I can buy at any pharmacy); it's doing me good and it costs a lot less. Interestingly, my kinesiologist told me that although this product is very hyped, it almost always fails her tests on her clients. And that's even though, as she told me, it could sell well. She doesn't sell any products of this kind herself, nor does any competing products, so I trust her expertise.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: On this page, the product appears to be praised repeatedly by the same people, a year apart? The suspicion is that these people are "Eqology partners" simply promoting their product. (which you obviously can't get out of, or only by paying a cancellation fee equal to the value of the products until the end of the term), which can only be terminated by phone using an Austrian number. (Source: Eqology website) If you recruit three new people and *they* then buy the exact same product as you, you don't pay for your (incredibly expensive) products the following month. (Source: Eqology website). Eqology partners who publicly complain about "Big Pharma" and then confidently promote "network marketing" (source: Facebook, LinkedIn, among others) as if they were doing you a personal favor... just seems extremely dubious.

REVIEW: I cancelled my subscription on 31.3.25 after just under a month, when I read about Eqology on Trustpilot. I paid Eqology 500 kr to cancel my subscription early, and the money was withdrawn from my account today. However, I am afraid that Eqology - as other customers also write on Trustpilot - will continue to withdraw money from my account, even though the subscription has been cancelled. If that happens (I would also recommend this to other customers who cannot cancel their Eqology subscription), I will contact the Consumer Ombudsman and file an objection with my bank. According to the Danish Sales Act, Eqology is not allowed to withdraw money from people's debit cards, and they are also not allowed to send orders to customers without the customer's consent when the subscription has been cancelled. I would have liked to have stopped the last order, but that was not possible, as according to Eqology the order had already been sent. So now they are withdrawing 1085 kr for my order and cancellation. I will undoubtedly make use of the consumer ombudsman and file an objection with my bank if I hear more from Eqology.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil
REVIEW: Stay FAR AWAY from this company. If they make a mistake, don't expect it to be fixed. I had signed up for a subscription to their fish oil and was supposed to receive an Omega 3 test with the latest delivery. However, they had forgotten to send it in the package, and when I pointed it out, I was asked, thank God, to fill out a form and sign under penalty of perjury that I had not received the shipment - that is, the package itself that I had received, but which was simply missing the test. What the hell is going on with you, Eqology? It is absolutely crazy that I am required to sign a form that I have not received the package that I have received - and even more so that you refuse to send the test that I have purchased and paid for before you have received the form back. Why is it that it should be MY responsibility that you have made a mistake? Eqology apparently believes it is entitled to refuse to send the test as long as I have not returned the form - and apologizes that it is their "procedure". You have to look for nonsense like that for a long time. How about just delivering the goods that your customers have purchased and paid for? I really have a hard time understanding why Eqology chooses to behave so arrogantly - as if they believe they are above the law on sales. As I said: Stay far away from this amateur company.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil

I should have listened to all my acquaintances who said that this is a pyramid scheme. Thought I've defended this company, I've had enough now!

The fact that I ultimately opted for the fine was due to the lack of reasonable alternatives on your part, not because I considered this to be an acceptable solution. I will certainly have my allergy further investigated in the future. Hence my review: I wanted to share my experience and the unfairness of the situation.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil

This is not only a huge extra burden (think of the time, costs for the doctor and possible blood tests), but also downright unreasonable. As a solution, I was told that otherwise I would have to pay a fine of €60 for canceling the subscription early. This feels like a punishment for something I can't do anything about! Furthermore, in my first order I paid for a test that I would only receive in the fifth month. Now that I have canceled the subscription, I hear nothing about it at all. This feels like a money grab. I find it bizarre how unreasonable Eqology is with customers who have a health problem. Instead of empathy and a solution, you get bureaucratic demands and extra costs. I would absolutely not recommend Eqology to others.

NAME: Pure Arctic Oil

These even have a better TOTOX value and also taste better. In addition, the test that Eqology includes is not reliable. You then take more fish oil than otherwise prescribed, logically it increases. In addition, the results are not indicated in values ​​but in colors on a line. The test is then not easy to interpret but mainly an influence. You actually do not really know what the result means for you. Unfortunately, I now know too many people who pay through the nose for Eqology. And then are also stuck with a subscription.

Just bite into the capsule and test how "good" this fish oil tastes. Almost all products are either chemically processed or "diluted" with cheap oil. It's quite simple for the consumer: simply compare the DHA and EPA values, which must be stated everywhere and are the key. To do this, only use products that are bioavailable (i.e., not capsules) and that offer a test (after about 5 months, the red blood cells are replaced, and when you then do a second blood test, you'll know how it helped). I don't know of any pharmacy product that offers a test, and you might well wonder why. NAME: Ultimate  Omega
REVIEW: Foreword: unfortunately I don't eat enough fish in my diet and the times I eat it it's not even very fresh (I live in Brescia) so it's important for me to supplement with these softgels. Another important reason that leads me to integrate Omega 3 is that I run about 40/45 km per week and therefore I am subject to pain and inflammation related to “post-activity”: Omega 3 have anti-inflammatory properties that help me to burn and do not involve side effects. I have been ingesting 2 softgels in the morning when I have breakfast for about 7/8 days and I confirm that during the digestive phase I have NOT felt any “return” of fish in my mouth: I would say an excellent result. The EPA-DHA percentages reach a good level, provided, however, that you ingest 2 tablets, there are products that do better, I would like to point out that the most important certification for Omega 3 is absent: the “IFOS” (International Fish Oil Standards). This certification has an analysis protocol issued by an independent body that has the necessary technologies to test the quality of raw materials and production processes: only Omega 3 that obtain the prestigious score of 5 IFOS stars derive exclusively from pure, uncontaminated, certified fish oil obtained through ultrafiltration and molecular distillation. These certifications are mentioned by the manufacturer: 'Purity tested' + 'Igen' + 'Friend of sea' which, however, are much less important than the 'IFOS'. Conclusions: on the importance of integrating with Omega 3 I think we are all in agreement, regarding this product, however, I believe that the sales cost of about 88€ (at the time of the review) is excessive compared to the competition that uses the IFOS certification.

These soft gels seem to hold their shape well and I find them easy to swallow. Better yet they don't give a fishy aftertaste or give you 'fish burps' as my nephew would describe them. I got this supplement to help with brain and heart health. I don't eat a lot of fish and don't have much omega-3 in my diet so supplementation is best for me. I also like that they're lab-tested, soy-free, gluten-free, and non-GMO, ticking all the boxes for quality and safety, which I am always careful about. Despite the size of the tablets, the benefits and lack of fishy taste make these a solid 5/5 for me.

NAME: Ultimate  Omega
REVIEW: Stepping into the world of Omega-3 supplements can feel a bit like navigating a dense forest, but my latest adventure with Nordic Naturals Ultimate Omega-3, boasting a hefty 1280mg dose and a cheeky lemon twist, turned out to be more of a leisurely stroll through a citrus grove. Let's dive into the nitty-gritty of why this little jar of sunshine has become a staple on my kitchen counter. The Tangy Taste Test: Right, let's address the elephant in the room - or rather, the lemon. The lemon flavour is a game-changer. No, not in the earth-shattering, life-altering way, but it's a pleasant departure from the fishy burps that haunt the memories of anyone who's ever dared to venture into Omega-3 territory. It's like someone at Nordic Naturals thought, "How do we make fish oil not taste like fish oil?" and then actually nailed it. Bravo! Dose Matters: With 1280mg of Omega-3, these softgels don't mess around. It's a high dose, sure, but it's exactly what the doctor ordered for someone like me who's trying to stay ahead in the health game, balancing a busy life with a small baby at home. It's like having a nutritional secret weapon in your arsenal, minus the need for a secret handshake. Softgels vs. The World: The 120 softgels come in a size that's manageable, even for someone who doesn't particularly love swallowing pills. They're like little lemon drops of health, sliding down with ease - a far cry from those horse pills that make you question your life choices as you try to swallow them. Pros: Lemon Flavour: Makes taking your daily Omega-3 not just bearable, but actually pleasant. High Dose: For those looking to really up their Omega-3 intake, this hits the spot. Quality: Nordic Naturals has a rep for purity and sustainability, which means less worrying about where your supplements are coming from. No Fishy Burps: Enough said. Cons: Pricey: Good quality comes at a price, and these are on the pricier side. But can you really put a price on not having fish-flavoured burps? Size: While manageable, the softgels are on the larger side. Not a deal-breaker, but worth noting for the pill-averse. In the grand scheme of things, Nordic Naturals Ultimate Omega-3 has found its way into my heart (and my daily routine) with its lemony zest and high-strength formula. It's a straightforward, no-nonsense supplement that delivers on its promises, and honestly, in a world full of overcomplicated health trends, that's as refreshing as a cool breeze on a hot summer's day. Whether you're a fellow parent trying to juggle life's responsibilities or just someone looking to boost your health, these Omega-3 softgels might just be the citrusy sidekick you didn't know you needed.

NAME: Omega 3
REVIEW: Let me be clear from the start: when a supplement like this arrives in poor condition — with capsules clumped, misshapen, and an inner seal already broken — it can completely destroy the product’s potential benefits and may even do more harm than good. With something like fish oil, where freshness and purity are essential, oxidation or degradation can make it not only ineffective, but potentially pro-inflammatory, which is the opposite of what you want from omega-3s. I had high hopes for this product given its clean formulation and solid EPA/DHA dosage. But honestly, none of that matters if the product arrives compromised. In my case, the outer plastic neck seal was intact — but the foil seal under the lid was partially open right out of the box, which is a huge red flag. The capsules were clumped together in a solid block inside the bottle, clearly due to heat or poor storage. When I finally got one loose, it was misshapen, not uniform — again, signs of damage.  When fish oil capsules stick together like this or lose their shape, it often means they’ve been exposed to excessive heat, which can cause the oil inside to oxidize or go rancid. That completely defeats the purpose — instead of supporting heart, brain, and skin health, you could be ingesting degraded oil that stresses your system. Before buying, I saw other reviewers mention similar issues — but I took the gamble. It backfired. To make things worse, the item was initially marked as “not eligible for return”. I had to dig through Amazon support and speak to a bot via callback to finally get a refund — minus a small deduction. It got sorted, but it was far from smooth. 🔴 Bottom line: If a product can’t be trusted to arrive sealed, fresh, and intact — then no matter how good the label looks, it’s not worth it. I won’t risk taking these, and I won’t be ordering again unless these serious quality control issues are resolved. There are better options out there, even if they cost a bit more — because you can’t put a price on your health.

NAME: Omega 3
REVIEW: Nutravita’s Omega 3 2000mg with 660mg EPA and 440mg DHA is one of the few supplements I’ve tried that actually justifies a place in my daily routine. What makes it stand out is not just the strength of the formulation, but the thoughtfulness behind the ingredients and sourcing. Each serving provides a potent dose of omega-3 fatty acids – particularly EPA and DHA – which are widely recognised for supporting heart health, brain function, vision, and overall inflammation control. Over the months I’ve been taking it, I’ve noticed subtle but genuine improvements in mental clarity, less stiffness post-workout, and a generally more balanced feeling in terms of focus and mood. That said, like most omega-3 products, the benefits build gradually over time – it’s not a quick fix, but a long-term helper. The capsules themselves are softgels that go down easily. They’re a bit on the larger side, but I’ve never had issues swallowing them with water. Best of all, they don’t cause any of those dreaded fishy burps or indigestion, which is more than I can say for some cheaper alternatives I’ve tested. The fish oil is sustainably sourced from the Peruvian coast and purified to remove heavy metals and other contaminants. It’s reassuring to know that you’re not ingesting any hidden nasties, and I really appreciate that it’s made here in the UK under GMP and BRC certification. That adds an extra layer of confidence in both quality and consistency. There are quite a few advantages that pushed me to stick with this supplement. For one, you’re getting 240 softgels per bottle, which translates into a full four-month supply. That’s excellent value, especially considering the high EPA and DHA levels. The formulation is also free from gluten, lactose, nuts and GMOs, making it a solid option for people with dietary restrictions. It’s backed by EFSA-approved health claims, which gives some weight to its promises. I also like the transparency in labelling and the fact that Nutravita has helpful, UK-based customer service in case any questions pop up. However, there are some things to keep in mind. This product is made with fish oil and bovine gelatine, so it’s absolutely not suitable for vegans or vegetarians. Also, while it doesn’t repeat on me, the capsules are not enteric-coated, which might be a downside for those with extremely sensitive digestion. The bottle has a mild fish smell when first opened – not a big deal, but worth noting. I’ve also seen some competitors combining fish oil with additional vitamins like D3 or K2, which this doesn’t include. And while two softgels per day is manageable, some may prefer a one-a-day solution for convenience. That said, this product is ideal for people who don’t eat much oily fish – which, realistically, is most of us. It’s great for adults who want to support cardiovascular health, cognitive function, or joint flexibility. Athletes or those in physically demanding jobs could benefit from its anti-inflammatory effects, and it may also help people experiencing dry eyes or mental fatigue. On the flip side, if you’re already consuming fish two or three times a week, or if you’re strictly plant-based, this may not be necessary. And of course, anyone on blood-thinning medication should speak to their doctor before adding a high-strength omega-3 like this. In the end, Nutravita’s Omega 3 fish oil delivers a clean, strong, no-nonsense product that’s affordable, effective, and easy to take. It’s not flashy, but it does the job – and does it well enough that I’ve reordered multiple times and plan to keep it in my routine. For less than £20 for four months of high-grade EPA and DHA, it’s one of the more trustworthy omega-3 supplements currently on the UK market.

NAME: Omega 3
REVIEW: Edit: For those wondering what it does, EPA (Eicosapentaenoic Acid): is known for its anti-inflammatory properties, it helps support heart health by maintaining healthy triglyceride levels, promoting better circulation, and potentially reducing the risk of heart disease. It may also help with joint health and mood regulation. DHA (Docosahexaenoic Acid): Critical for brain function and eye health. It's a major structural component of the brain and retina, helping with cognitive performance, memory, and visual development. How much do you need? General Health: 250–500mg combined EPA & DHA daily. Heart Health & High Triglycerides: 1000mg+ daily. Brain Health & Pregnancy: 500–1000mg daily (200–300mg DHA for pregnancy). What you get: One serving (2 capsules) provides 1100mg EPA & DHA, which is more than enough for general well-being. Taking 1 capsule gives 550mg, ideal if you already get some omega-3s from your diet, I take 2 anyway. I take Nutrivita 2000mg omega 3 alongside Viridian's high five and NutriGeek's lion's mane & black pepper extract for maximum absorption and general health + brain boost. I've been taking these for 3 weeks+ and of course, it's hard to quantify how well supplements affects you personally, but hey, most of us probably need the boosts. The softgels are about average size, easy to swallow, has a slight dry fish smell (not bad at all), tasteless and no burps either. It's sustainable, fair price, large supply, decent strength, it's stored in a dark recyclable plastic bottle to minimize oxidation, clear instructions in different EU languages. All in all, it's a good product to keep your omega 3 intake high.

REVIEW: This product is apparently no different from what they sell you in pharmacies by packaging it from the bulk one that they collect in packs of thousands of softgels. It stems from the appropriate processing of fish oil resulting from industrial processing (...) and, for the moment, I cannot say that I have disorders of any kind, always taking it after the two main meals. Let's get straight to the point: on the Amazon site (I saved the various screenshots) it is said that the oil comes from South American fish (Peru to be exact) but the back of the published label does not show the origin which, on the other hand, appears in clear letters in the Italian label that I photographed: CHINA. Now, just to want to be rational and guaranteed, the country of origin is not in itself symptomatic of quality, but if that really were the case why advertise something different and not show the actual Italian label on Amazon? Since, dear gentlemen, we are not talking about a charger but about a supplement that goes INSIDE OUR BODY, I believe it is our sacrosanct right to obtain respect and transparency not only from multinational drug companies (.. no comment...) but also and above all from “family-run companies”, however, of a country now outside the EU, which would never be responsible for damage caused to our health. I expect a documented reply from the manufacturer/importer and I reserve the right to stimulate appropriate investigations also for other supplements of dubious origin, giving small companies the benefit of the doubt and a wide right of reply before taking action. And rest assured that, if you find me “good-natured” in reviewing the cat's scratching post, my attention will be maximum on this kind of article. Of the same item code, I saw and saved the photo attached to a negative review, with SLOVENIA as the country of origin. You will understand that behind these infinite triangulations of suppliers it is very difficult to trace the real manufacturer so either the British Authority certifies fried air or the product is not original. Well... Of course, it could also be that the label contains incorrect data, that they have trimmed a batch of “oil” suitably reprocessed in China or... better not to think about it. In short, anything can be. When in doubt, the consumer must be protected. The two stars concern, as a precautionary measure, the current “subjective” situation, but, in the absence of a specific and documented response within 30 days, I will write to Amazon and the GdF., protecting (me and you) to the fullest extent of the law. E. Obviously, I do not return the purchased product because it can be used as a test. If you agree with my objective, I appreciate a like. As for the use of this type of supplement, I decided to switch to krill oil from a different source, with the clarification that it is used mainly for triglycerides, which derive from the metabolism of sugars and carbohydrates, not from the consumption of eggs, which, on the other hand, has been reevaluated by recent medical guidelines (we are talking about fresh eggs from healthy animals raised in a natural way, of course...). NAME: OMEGA 3 Fish Oil 2000mg
REVIEW: The dark plastic jar arrived intact and after removing the seals it did not give off any smell. It contains 240 beads. The SINGLE pearl consists of an external bovine gelatin capsule and 1000 mg of internal oil that SHOULD contain 330 mg of EPA, 220 mg of DHA, vitamin E and 450 mg of unknown substance (perhaps water and glycerin). If true, these values of EPA and DHA are average/high compared to many competitors who generally offer 180 mg of EPA and 120 mg of DHA. The visible label, however, is a bit ambiguous about the composition of the individual pearl, suggesting otherwise. The expiration of the product is long (in my case 2026). The product does not have any specific quality certification such as IFOS or GOED. The pearls, which may seem large, are easily ingested because they are very slippery, tasteless and without any aftertaste. The Omega 3 contained are in the LEAST bioavailable form, that is, in the form of Ethyl Ester, like many other Omega 3. The production company is located in China, while the clients are Irish and English. Does the Omega 3 integration work? From many international and accredited studies it would seem so. Do these Omega-3s work? Personally, I haven't felt any benefit and I can't say that the improvements (cholesterol, blood sugar and triglycerides) documented by my blood tests are solely due to this supplement. It does not seem to me that this brand has independent and accredited certificates that attest that the quality and quantity of the ingredients written on the label are actually present in the pearl... I remind you that in the European Union all supplements are regulated as foods and not as medicines and therefore must comply only with food regulations. I have no interest in this review.

NAME: Super Strength
REVIEW: This listing is inaccurate and contains several misleading claims. The active ingredients in Omega-3 supplements are EPA and DHA, so a higher-strength product should contain a higher percentage of these essential fatty acids—not just a larger overall volume of oil. In ZipVit’s case, the product contains 33% EPA and 22% DHA, but these values are misleadingly stated per two capsules, not per one, which is contrary to how most reputable brands present this information. This misrepresents the actual strength of each capsule. Another, more serious concern is the lack of transparency in the product labelling. Food supplements are required to include the manufacturing location for traceability and regulatory compliance. However, this product does not provide a manufacturing address—only that of a UK distributor. Saying it has a "UK Supplier" is irrelevant, as almost everything sold in the UK would have one. Not even origin information is disclosed! The ingredient list is also vague. It states: Fish Oil, Mixed Tocopherols, Capsule Shell, Glycerine, Purified Water—but does not clarify the source of the capsule shell. Is it bovine (beef), porcine (pork), or marine/vegan? This information is important and should be clearly disclosed. Is it suitable for vegans, vegetarians? It is not suitable for neither. More reputable brands will clearly indicate the origin of the gelatin. Does this brand have any certifications? When was the last time amazon checked their certifications? Due to the poor and misleading labelling, I did not even proceed to check the smell, taste, or size of the capsules. Unfortunately, this item will be going in the bin. I’ll be purchasing from more reputable brands that are transparent about their formulations and manufacturing practices. Amazon get a grip on this category!!! Update  The company reached out and assured me that the item is manufactured in the UK and their Omega 3 product is Friend of the Sea certified. They will be improving their product labelling. This is why I upgraded their feedback from 1 star to 3 stars. I think with the new label they will be a better choice than many on amazon.

NAME: Super Strength
REVIEW: As all other fish oil sellers do, this company is no exception. It labels the strength as 2000mg which misleads the buyer into thinking that each gel is 2000 mg, but no, it is 1000mg per gel. 'Per serving' is not a standard measurement. You have to read the small print at the back. As buyers are accustomed to 'one-a-day' serving, they naturally think that 120 capsules will last 120 days with 2000mg a day, but no, it is 1000mg for 120 days or 2000 mg for 60 days. You are effectively buying half the amount 'per serving'. Advertising 120 capsules together with 2000mg is misleading. If you sellers want to advertise 'per serving' then say that it is 2000mg per servicing and 60 servings, not switch between measurements. Another misleading label is 'Super strength'. They are the standard 1000mg capsules. This issue is happening with other sellers as well, not to pick on this seller in particular. I just wrote here because I bought from this seller. This attitude is not good for the reputation and trustworthiness of the company. Another issue is that the bag doesn't seal after a while of daily use. The seal is very fine and not durable. As to the capsules themselves, there are no issues. They are good.

NAME: Super Strength
REVIEW: Many Omega 3 fish oil distributors have resorted to making their product descriptions wholly misleading and ZipVit is one of them. It seems that people like to buy "strong" products, so distributors use meaningless terms such as "High Strength", "High Potency" and, in ZipVit's case, "Super Strength". These terms are meaningless because they are not defined. Is Super Strength stronger than High Strength? We just don't know. These terms are used to confuse, not to inform. The active ingredients in Omega 3 products are EPA and DHA. So a higher strength product should have a higher percentage of these essential fatty acids than a lower strength product. In fact, ZipVit's product is 33% EPA and 22% DHA. That is exactly the same as Superself's product and Nutravita's product. It is slightly better than Seven Sea's product which is 30% EPA and 20% DHA. And these brands are better than Amazon's own product, branded as Solimo, which manages 26% EPA and 18% DHA. But the highest strength I have found so far is the Inessa brand which delivers 40% EPA and 30% DHA. The lowest strength I have found so far is the PlusVIVE brand at 18% EPA and 12% DHA, yet it is still described as High Strength! Here is a simple idea for these distributors, stop using these misleading and dishonest descriptions and just tell us amount of EPA and DHA you deliver per capsule. Simple.  The next marketing trick is even worse. Instead of telling us clearly the quantity of EPA and DHA per capsule, they tell us the amount of EPA and DHA per "serving size" and a serving size could be 1, 2, 3 or more capsules. ZipVit's headline is "Omega 3 Fish Oil 2000mg, EPA 660mg DHA 440mg per Daily Serving. 120 Capsules (2 Months Supply). Supports Heart, Brain Function and Eye Health. 2 Capsules Per Serving". I'll wager most people will read this and conclude each capsule contains 2000mg and delivers 660mg EPA and 440mg of DHA. And the proof of that is the number of people who write reviews and bitterly complain they were deceived. Check the other reviews here! If you read a bit further, you will see the headline says, "120 Capsules (2 months Supply)". If you read that far and DO THE MATH, you will realise you are being advised to take two capsules per day. But does that mean you will get 2 x 2000mg per day? Or is a single capsule 1000mg so you only get 2000mg per day? Nowhere does ZipVit state the product delivers 1000mg per capsule. Nowhere. If you get this far and are confused, you might decide to look at the photos to see if the labelling on the bottle clarifies matters. It seems to. The last image says, "Super Strength Omega 3 Fish Oil 2000mg". OK, that's clear then, nothing here about serving size. It must be 2000mg per capsule. Except it is not. If you look at the other product images, you see five images of the front of the bottle but they are all oriented so you can read "Super Strength Omega 3 Fish Oil 2000mg" but it is impossible to read the words "(per serving)" that follow. Unfortunate accident or intentionally misleading? Of course, ZipVit cannot actually lie--that is illegal. But misleading the hell out of us is not. And ZipVit pulls every trick in the book to mislead us. ZipVit is not the only company that uses this dishonest approach--several of them pull the same stunt. Earlier, I mentioned the Inessa brand which is the highest strength Omega fish oil I have found on Amazon. Their headline is refreshingly clear and simple, "Omega 3 Fish Oil 1200mg (480mg EPA/360mg DHA per Capsule)". Perfect. Why can't ZipVit adopt the same unambiguous approach? Why can't you ZipVit? Finally, Amazon has a responsibility here as the company that is selling these products. Amazon should refuse to stock products that employ misleading product descriptions. If they did that, I have a hunch companies like ZipVit would suddenly see the error of their ways. How about it Amazon?

I hadn't really put it down to taking this until I looked back when I started. My skin was a lot softer and hair seemed thicker (though not sure if this was an effect). I did also notice I was feeling a bit sharper mentally and at work too. Could be a mix of other things but will continue taking them. I bought originally last year had about an 8 month break in taking and noticed the change then. After taking them again I could see significat improvemnts. I will be sticking with these. I have put a photo of the pill itself as they are quite big if you have no issues taking supplements. If you are a deep researcher you might find this useful too: This brand offers both EPA (600mg) and DHA (440mg) They are two types of omega-3 fatty acids found in fish oil. EPA - For anti inflamatory effects and great for heart health, joint support and mood regulation. DHA - which I have been taking for years separately - especially great for brain function, eye health and nervous system support. Plays a big role in memory focus and cognitive developement. They are both a decent amount. Others are much lower. In summary - I wish I had this info before. It would have saved me some time finding a top product. My only concern is that it won't be available or our of stock as when I have found something good in the past, it often just dissapears. For now though - this one has been arond for some time. I hope this has helped. Highly recommend.
